[01:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'headquarters of Phantom Neuro. It\'s building&nbsp; what\'s known as a muscle computer interface.&nbsp;&nbsp; In the most basic [music] terms, Phantom has made&nbsp; sensors that translate Alex\'s intention to move&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into actual movements on his robotic hand.&nbsp; To explain in more detail, may I introduce&nbsp;&nbsp; Phantom\'s lustroushaired founder and CEO, Connor&nbsp; Glass? I\'m Connor Glass. I\'m the founder and CEO&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of Phantom Neuro. I went through medical school&nbsp; and was extremely passionate about function&nbsp;&nbsp; limiting injuries. So people with functional&nbsp; disabilities who can\'t do whatever it is that&nbsp;&nbsp; they want [music] to do. Uh and I recognized that&nbsp; there was really a gap in the market in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'commercially relevant approaches to human [music]&nbsp; machine interfacing. Almost all of the commercial&nbsp;&nbsp; focus was on brain computer interface which is&nbsp; fantastic. But it actually turns out that the vast&nbsp;&nbsp; majority of people with physical disabilities&nbsp; [music] don\'t have to have a brain implant in&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'order to regain their loss function through human&nbsp; [music] machine interfacing. So ultimately we came&nbsp;&nbsp; up with this implantable sensor system for&nbsp; the limbs that could do the same thing as a&nbsp;&nbsp; brain computer interface but in the setting of&nbsp; outpatient surgery. Very straightforward. You&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t need [music] a specialized surgeon. Phantom&nbsp; fits into the shoving electrodes into your body&nbsp;&nbsp; field. Companies like Neurolink and Onward have&nbsp; been building implants for the brain and spine.&nbsp;&nbsp; This technology can help people suffering&nbsp; from paralysis or ALS speak, use computers,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and even walk again. But instead of putting a&nbsp; chip in someone\'s brain, Phantom [music] has&nbsp;&nbsp; built a device that gets implanted right&nbsp; next to the person\'s amputation site.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So this is what would go under somebody\'s arm&nbsp; right under the skin. But you can either have a&nbsp;&nbsp; wearable armband or you can have an implantable&nbsp; armband. And so the goal is to have a ring of&nbsp;&nbsp; sensors around your limb. And so what we do is we&nbsp; put two of these devices in somebody. [music] One&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'goes on top of the arm or residual limb and one&nbsp; goes on the bottom. And then these are wireless&nbsp;&nbsp; electronics, right? that\'s sending the signals&nbsp; out to this edge compute kind of module we have&nbsp;&nbsp; called the fusion port and that\'s what\'s actually&nbsp; computing [music] and then telling the robotic&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wrist and hand what to do. So we make the implant&nbsp; or this wearable uh as well as the edge compute&nbsp;&nbsp; module. So these two black boxes that you\'re&nbsp; seeing here have this exact chip on the inside&nbsp;&nbsp; of it. So these are just the the simulators cuz&nbsp; it\'s not implanted. The earliest people using&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Phantom\'s technology like Alex have had external&nbsp; sensors placed around their amputation site.&nbsp;&nbsp; Phantom though is in the midst of running&nbsp; clinical trials [music] where its device&nbsp;&nbsp; will be implanted right under the skin. We have&nbsp; a wearable system and that\'s what\'s allowed us to&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'optimize [music] our implantable system which will&nbsp; be implanted at the beginning of next year. And so&nbsp;&nbsp; what we do is is you make a pocket under the skin&nbsp; that basically is the [music] size of the implant&nbsp;&nbsp; and then you put the implant under the skin in&nbsp; that pocket. So it\'s very straightforward. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s much more like a cosmetic procedure [music]&nbsp; where you don\'t need general anesthesia. And so,&nbsp;&nbsp; it should be less than an hourong procedure.&nbsp; You know, maybe 15 to 30 minutes for someone to&nbsp;&nbsp; walk in, [music] get these things put under their&nbsp; skin, wrap them up, and then they\'re out the door.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:36] [scene:talk]
